<subSubSection id="44813FA5D560FFA5A5FD0C92FD569001" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" type="description">
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0C92FB8E9625" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">D e s c r i p t i o n. Female brachypterous. Body dark brown except prothorax yellowish brown, meso- and metathorax yellow, fore tarsi pale yellow, and the base of antennal segments III and IV pale brown. Antennal segments V and VI darker than other segments, like as abdominal segments. Wings including scale are pale. All setae dark brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0D12FDD394E5" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
Head wider than length (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A7280D12FDA19645" box="[526,590,303,330]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 2</figureCitation>
); basal half with transverse reticulations; compound eyes with 6 pigmented facets; three small ocelli present, three pairs of ocellar setae present; ocellar setae pair III longest and situated on anterior margins of ocellar triangle; 4 pairs of postocular setae present, pair III longest (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A7E40DB2FCEB96A5" box="[706,772,399,426]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Mouth cone short, reaching to fore coxae. Maxillary palps 3-segmented. Antennae 8-segmented, with forked sense cone on antennal segments III and IV, segment VI pedicellate; segments III–VI with microtrichia on both dorsal and ventral view (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A7080DD2FD879505" box="[558,616,495,522]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Pronotum strongly transverse, surface sculptured with widely spaced transverse striae, irregular at middle; with one long seta on each posterior angles; posterior margin with four pairs of setae (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A6420E12FC4E9545" box="[868,929,559,586]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 3</figureCitation>
); pronotum with at least 12–14 short discal setae. Ferna divided medially (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A6260E72FCAF9565" box="[768,832,591,618]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum transverse, with a pair of campaniform sensilla at anterior margin; metascutum irregularly reticulate, with median setae far from anterior margin (at middle of sclerite), metanotal campaniform sensilla absent (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A4400E92FE4695C5" box="[358,425,687,714]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 4</figureCitation>
); mesosternum with spinula, metasternum without spinula. Tarsi 2-segmented. Abdominal tergites I–VIII with transverse sculpture medially (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A13B0EF2FBB795E5" box="[1053,1112,719,746]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 6</figureCitation>
), without ctenidia laterally; posteromarginal craspeda present on tergites II–VIII (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A6D00ED2FBDB9405" box="[1014,1076,751,778]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 6</figureCitation>
); abdominal tergites I–VIII with a pair of campaniform sensilla on posterior margin, median setae wider apart than their length; tergite VIII without comb on posterior margin, tergite IX without sculpture lines, with two pairs of campaniform sensilla; tergite X with complete median split. Setae S6 on tergites II–VII inserted on pleurotergite. Abdominal sternites without discal setae (except sternite II with one discal seta); sternite II with 2 pairs, III–VII with 3 pairs of marginal setae; sternites II–VII with broad craspedum on posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="94A070ABD560FFA5A5880FF2FF0394E5" box="[174,236,975,1002]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[194,1221,352,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[174,1233,335,1722]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–7. Eryngyothrips veisii sp. n.: 1 — antenna; 2 — head; 3 — pronotum; 4 — metascutum; 5 — ferna; 6 — abdominal tergite VI; 7 — abdominal sternite IV." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452600/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor well developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0FD2FD799385" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
Measurements (
<typeStatus id="D320D28CD560FFA5A4B90FD2FDE79305" box="[415,520,1007,1034]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">holotype</typeStatus>
in microns). Body distended length 1200. Head length (width) 87 (134). Pronotum length (width) 96 (175); posteroangular setae 40. Fore wing length (median width) 90 (50). Abdominal tergite tergite IX S1 setae 90, S2 setae 100. Antennal segments I–VIII length (width) I 17 (26), II 30 (24), III 42 (18), IV 40 (19), V 32 (19), VI 43 (18), VII 9 (6), and VIII 14 (4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD08B2FE5B93A5" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" box="[219,436,1167,1194]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">M a l e. Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0892FD0E92C5" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
R e m a r k s. Ferna are attached (undivided) in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A6330892FBF893C5" box="[789,1047,1199,1226]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A6330892FC5893C6" box="[789,951,1199,1225]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Eryngyothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, except in this new species and 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A44B08EDFE0493E6" baseAuthorityName="zur Strassen" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[365,491,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nickelae">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A44B08EDFE0493E6" box="[365,491,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. nickelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(zur 
<bibRefCitation id="680A11DFD560FFA5A70D08F2FD3893E5" author="Strassen, R." box="[555,727,1231,1258]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" pagination="1 - 271" refId="ref2063" refString="zur Strassen, R. 2003. Die terebranten Thysanopteren Europas und des Mittelmeer-Gebietes. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, 74, 1 - 271." type="journal article" year="2003">Strassen, 2003</bibRefCitation>
), but according to the key by zur 
<bibRefCitation id="680A11DFD560FFA5A14E08F2FEC19205" author="Strassen, R." pageId="2" pageNumber="473" pagination="1 - 271" refId="ref2063" refString="zur Strassen, R. 2003. Die terebranten Thysanopteren Europas und des Mittelmeer-Gebietes. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, 74, 1 - 271." type="journal article" year="2003">Strassen (2003: 241)</bibRefCitation>
, the new species is readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A67208CDFC3E9206" baseAuthorityName="zur Strassen" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[852,977,1263,1289]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nickelae">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A67208CDFC3E9206" box="[852,977,1263,1289]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. nickelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the color of body (in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A5E8092DFEA79226" baseAuthorityName="zur Strassen" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[206,328,1295,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nickelae">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A5E8092DFEA79226" box="[206,328,1295,1321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. nickelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
body color dark brown versus bicolored in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A61B092DFC7B9226" authority="Mirab-balou &amp; Bazgir &amp; Mahmoodi, 2015" authorityName="Mirab-balou &amp; Bazgir &amp; Mahmoodi" authorityYear="2015" box="[829,916,1296,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veisii" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A61B092DFC7B9226" box="[829,916,1296,1321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. veisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="25DC0D47D560FFA5A6BF0932FC399225" box="[921,982,1295,1322]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) and posteroangular setae (in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A429090DFE649246" baseAuthorityName="zur Strassen" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[271,395,1327,1353]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nickelae">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A429090DFE649246" box="[271,395,1327,1353]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. nickelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this is pale versus dark in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A799090DFCF89246" authority="Mirab-balou &amp; Bazgir &amp; Mahmoodi, 2015" authorityName="Mirab-balou &amp; Bazgir &amp; Mahmoodi" authorityYear="2015" box="[703,791,1328,1353]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veisii" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A799090DFCF89246" box="[703,791,1328,1353]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. veisii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="25DC0D47D560FFA5A6380912FCB39245" box="[798,860,1327,1354]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
), and sternites III–VII without discal setae (vs. with many discal setae in 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A7BC0972FD179266" baseAuthorityName="zur Strassen" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[666,760,1359,1385]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nickelae">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A7BC0972FD179266" box="[666,760,1359,1385]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">nickelae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). According to color of body, this new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A4C2094DFD5B9285" authority="Bhatti" authorityName="Bhatti" authorityYear="1979" box="[484,692,1391,1418]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A4C2094DFD8F9286" box="[484,608,1391,1417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. discolor</emphasis>
Bhatti
</taxonomicName>
, but is readily distinguished from the latter by divided ferna, prothorax color yellowish brown, absence of metanotal campaniform sensilla, and the longest postocular setae pair III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD09F2FD8F9125" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
Recently, 
<taxonomicName id="CB9B17ADD560FFA5A47509EDFDFC92E6" box="[339,531,1487,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Eryngyothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banihashemii">
<emphasis id="3EEFB03CD560FFA5A47509EDFDFC92E6" box="[339,531,1487,1513]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E. banihashemii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from 
<collectingCountry id="748C2CBED560FFA5A63F09F2FCA492E5" box="[793,843,1487,1514]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Iran</collectingCountry>
(Minaeii et al., 2014), but this new species can be distinguished from latter by divided ferna, the color of legs, and no campaniform sensilla on metanotum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0A12FBDC9145" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" box="[219,1075,1583,1610]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">E t y m o l o g y. This species is named after its collector, Mr. Hamid Veisi.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C246C2ED560FFA5A5FD0A72FD769165" blockId="2.[166,1225,175,1642]" box="[219,665,1615,1642]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
D i s t r i b u t i o n. 
<collectingCountry id="748C2CBED560FFA5A4880A72FE0D9165" box="[430,482,1615,1642]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Iran</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion id="CE5FA2CCD560FFA5A4CB0A72FD7A9165" box="[493,661,1615,1642]" country="Iran" name="Ilam" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Ilam province</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
